  canonicalUrl="/fencing-contractors/missed-call-text-back/"
  channelName="Missed Call Text Back"
  tradeName="Fencing Contractor"
  tradeNamePlural="Fencing Contractors"
  tradeSlug="fencing-contractors"
  headline="Missed Call Text Back for UK Fencing Contractors"
  accentWord="Fencing Contractors"
  subhead="It is 9am on a Tuesday in November. Storm Babet was two days ago and your phone has not stopped ringing. You are on a job replacing six panels and two concrete posts at a property in Headington, postcrete setting around a plumbed post, both hands occupied. Three calls come in before 10am. Without Missed Call Text Back, three homeowners hear voicemail, two call other fencing companies, and you lose two potential jobs before you even check your phone. With it, all three receive an instant text — 'Thank you for calling, we are on a storm repair and will call you back shortly' — and all three wait."
  scenario="It is 2:30pm on a Saturday in late October. You have just finished a close board fence installation along a rear boundary in Didcot — posts concreted, rails attached, feather edge boards nailed and capped. You are loading tools into the van when you realise you had two missed calls during the last hour of the job — one at 1:45pm and one at 2:15pm. Without Missed Call Text Back, you listen to the voicemails. The first is a homeowner in Wallingford: 'Hi, just wondered if you could quote for a new fence, give me a ring back please.' There is no name. The second voicemail is blank — someone who hung up. You call the first number back but it goes straight to voicemail. The second number gives you nothing to work with. Both leads are effectively lost. With Missed Call Text Back, the 1:45pm caller received a text six seconds after hanging up: 'Thank you for calling [your company]. We are on a job and will call you back shortly. If you would like a quicker response, reply with your fencing requirements.' She replied at 1:48pm: 'Need about 12 metres of close board fencing with concrete posts down the left side of our rear garden. We are in Wallingford, OX10. Can you do a site visit this week?' The 2:15pm caller — who left a blank voicemail — also received the text and replied: 'Hi, just moved into a new build and the developer only put up cheap lapboard fence. Want to upgrade to proper close board. About 20 panels worth. Can you help?' At 2:35pm, sitting in the van, you see two lead summaries: one for 12 metres of close board in Wallingford with a midweek visit request, and one for a 20-panel lapboard-to-close-board upgrade in a new build. You call both within ten minutes and book surveys for Tuesday."
  benefits={benefits}
  faqs={faqs}
  channelPageUrl="/construction-trades/missed-call-text-back/"
  tradePageUrl="/fencing-contractors/ai-receptionist/"
  ctaHeadline="Recover Every Storm-Season Missed Call with a Text"
  ctaSubhead={`November through March, your missed call rate doubles. A text within seconds keeps every caller waiting for your callback. Add-on at £${pricing.addOn.price}/month.`}
